    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "7085da28_0b343168",
        "filename": "tests/SkSLGLSLTest.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 9
      },
      "lineNbr": 2576,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-31T18:38:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Does SkSL (or the underlying shading languages) assert that constructor arguments form sequence points? Even so, it seems like this would be easier to read if the initialization was moved to the declaration? (It might make the code to generate this simpler, too? By hoisting that logic out of the final loop?)",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 2576,
        "startChar": 14,
        "endLine": 2576,
        "endChar": 83
      },
      "revId": "f5460b21ad158f9c07b175e2f9e7b34d3607f563",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "69fb34a4_18e90506",
        "filename": "tests/SkSLGLSLTest.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 9
      },
      "lineNbr": 2576,
      "author": {
        "id": 5640
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-03T18:42:01Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "GLSL does guarantee evaluation order, and our SPIR-V output guarantees this ordering as well. Hoisting the assignment to the declaration means we\u0027re deliberately breaking execution order, and I\u0027ve generally been loathe to do so, hence the hoops I\u0027m jumping through to keep evaluation order intact here.\n\nBuuuut I should have considered that we now support Metal. After going through the Metal spec, I\u0027m pretty sure it inherits C++\u0027s lack of ordering guarantees, which means all of my hoop-jumping is pointless. This has been hoisted to the declaration now.",
      "parentUuid": "7085da28_0b343168",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 2576,
        "startChar": 14,
        "endLine": 2576,
        "endChar": 83
      },
      "revId": "f5460b21ad158f9c07b175e2f9e7b34d3607f563",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "21995664_1523ef40",
        "filename": "tests/SkSLGLSLTest.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 9
      },
      "lineNbr": 2576,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-03T18:49:44Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Didn\u0027t C++17 add in some left-to-right ordering guarantees for comma lists?\n(Not that I know what Metal actually promises)",
      "parentUuid": "69fb34a4_18e90506",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 2576,
        "startChar": 14,
        "endLine": 2576,
        "endChar": 83
      },
      "revId": "f5460b21ad158f9c07b175e2f9e7b34d3607f563",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ace0a80b_b52ecd4b",
        "filename": "tests/SkSLGLSLTest.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 9
      },
      "lineNbr": 2576,
      "author": {
        "id": 5640
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-03T18:54:15Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Metal is explicitly derived from C++14. That may change in the future, but right now we can\u0027t rely on ordering guarantees.",
      "parentUuid": "21995664_1523ef40",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 2576,
